text: i am going to test run bringing chewbacca in for a couple of hours, unless there are any objections

thank you for notifying us, James! I’m going to pin this note here that I emailed out a few months ago only to make sure people are aware + can easily reference dog related policies :slightly_smiling_face:

As we are growing and have a few new dogs in the studio these days, I wanted to remind everyone of Uncorked’s dog policy as well as address the barking issue we’ve been having. Please read these reminders and know that I will be strictly enforcing these rules moving forward.

-All dogs must meet other studio dogs for the first time off-site (in the parking lot, at a park, anywhere) prior to coming into the studio.
-Use <#C02GQA4FR|dogs> on slack to communicate when you will be bringing your dog into the studio, or to notify owners or any potential dog-related accidents/issues.
-All dog accidents are the responsibility of the dog owner.
-Dogs are not permitted to wander the studio or left unattended by the dog owner for any period of time.
-Even a single bark is distracting/disruptive to employees. If a dog continues to be disruptive, you will be asked to take your dog home.
-Dogs are not permitted to use our dishes - please use the metal dog dishes in the kitchen or bring your own.

As always, anyone can talk with me directly if you need to report a dog related issue. We understand that people value being able to bring their dogs into work, but it is imperative that these rules are adhered to so we are respectful to everyone. Further info can be found the Employee Handbook.

Every holiday (Xmas, bday, easter...) I asked for a dog.  Finally convinced my parents...she was an awesome dog and helped me get through my teenage years.  One of my moms favorite stories is that every time she scolded me, Shammy would ignore her for the rest of the day.
